AGI -&nbsp; After yesterday's darkness a light appears to emerge from the medical bulletin issued by the Vatican on the health of Pope Francis, admitted to the Gemini from February 14. Its conditions "permanent criticism" and the complexity of the clinical picture imposes "that the prognosis remains reserved". The novelty that worries is the emergence of a kidney failure but, it explains, is "lieve", in the "initial" phase and "under control". Since last night there have also been no "last respiratory crisis", although "oxytherapy continues with high flow through nasal cannulas".
&nbsp;
The transfusions of yesterday - today were not necessary - have improved the level of anemia, despite the lowering of the platelets remained stable. "You have carried out the two units of concentrated hemacies with benefit and with rise of the value of hemoglobin", you read in the medical bulletin. "Stable has remained the piastrinopenia." However, "some blood tests show an initial, slight, kidney failure, under control," he said. Obviously it is necessary to wait "so that pharmaceutical therapies can give some feedback".
<div </div
The situation remains critical but, compared to yesterday, the climate seems more relaxed. Pope Francis "continues to be vigilant and well oriented". "In the course of the morning, at the apartment set up on the 10th floor, he participated in the Holy Mass, together with those who take care of him in these days of death." This morning the Vatican press room reported that the night was spent quiet and that the Pontiff had rested.
&nbsp;
"I am confident that the reconstruction to the Policlinico Gemelli, carrying out the necessary care," the Pope said, through the text of the Angelus, which was only widespread. "Even rest is part of therapy!" Bergoglio thanked "heart" the doctors and health professionals of the Gemelli "for attention" and "the dedication with which they perform their service among the sick" and was said "particularly impressed" by the letters and drawings that children have given him, as the many messages of closeness and affection from all over the world. Thanks also expressed through social media, on X, where the Pope's posts were missing from February 16.
&nbsp;
In the text of the Angelus, the Pope did not miss his call for peace. Recalling that tomorrow is the third anniversary of the war in Ukraine "wonderful and shameful recurrence for the whole of humanity", he invited "to remember the victims of all armed conflicts and to pray for the gift of peace in Palestine, Israel and throughout the Middle East, in Myanmar, Kivu and Sudan".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In his homily, always prepared by him, for the Mass on the occasion of the Jubilee of the Diacons, he remarked that only forgiveness can help a world torn by hatred and wars. "A world where there is only hatred for the opponents is a world without hope, without future - it is the text of the homily read by Monsignor Rino Fisichella -, destined to be torn by wars, divisions and sold endlessly, as we unfortunately also see today, at many levels and in various parts of the world. To forgive, then, means to prepare for the future a welcoming, safe house, in us and in our communities". Finally, the invitation to the new deacons to be "apostoles of forgiveness" not to have "fear of risking love".
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, prayers for the health of Bergoglio have multiplied today. First, Monsignor Fisichella, who invited a "intensive" prayer for the Lord to assist Francis "at the time of trial and illness". The "his" diocese was also gathered in prayer. Cardinal Baldo Reina celebrated Mass in the Basilica of St. John in Lateran "with a special intercession for the health of Pope Francis" and the President of the Council, Cardinal Matteo Zuppi presided over the Rosary to ask God to support the Pope "at this time of suffering, so that he may find relief and be restored as soon as possible". &nbsp;
